<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance was cited as  <i>Viguiera parishii</i> Shrubland Alliance in the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>. The alliance has been expanded to include another characteristic species.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>is a semi-woody, many-branching shrub up to 1.5 m tall with woody, many-branched roots to 1.5 m in depth. Plants often occur on coarse-textured soils that may be moderately saline. Plants lose some leaves in the dry season and most in severe drought, and they turn reddish in color. Plants flower from early spring through summer. Seeds are dispersed by ants, wind, and water. Seed germination requires light, and seedling success is high in wet years (Montalvo 2002b). <br/>
<br/>
The varieties of <i>E. fasciculatum </i>vary in a combination of traits, especially color, chromosome number, leaf shape, leaf margins, and pubescence. They also show some geographic separation; var. <i>fasciculatum</i> is restricted to the Central Coast, while var. <i>flavoviride </i> grows in the Colorado, Mojave, Sonoran deserts and southeastern Great Basin.  Varieties <i>foliolosum </i> and <i>polifolium </i> are found in both cismontane and transmontane areas (UCB 2017). <br/>
<br/>
Little information exists on <i>Viguiera parishii</i> in the literature. This facultatively deciduous plant flowers profusely in rainy years and remains largely dormant and bare of leaves in dry years. It probably regenerates from a seed bank. Recent taxonomic literature considers this taxon a synonym of <i>Bahiopsis parishii </i>(UCB 2017).<br/>
<br/>
This alliance occurs in the desert transition along hills and mountains of the Mojave, Colorado, and Sonoran deserts along with <i>Yucca schidigera, Cylindropuntia acanthocarpa, Coleogyne ramosissima,</i> and related scrub. The character species are more widespread in southern California and hot deserts than is the alliance. Other associated species, such as <i>Bebbia juncea, Gutierrezia microcephala, </i>and <i>Salazaria mexicana, </i>suggest that the alliance is disturbance-related. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
