    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Stands straddle the upper desert/lower montane zone within the Peninsular Ranges and in Anza-Borrego State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ac-h, Aj-p). Stands in the eastern subsections occur in washes (Thomas et al. 2004). Stands mixed with several other shrub species also occur on rocky or bouldery granitic slopes at Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005, LaDoux et al. 2013). Stands are mapped in the Mesquite Valley (Veg Camp and AIS 2013) and surveyed throughout Mojave National Preserve and Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di-j). Stands occur on slopes above the northern Owens Valley and the lower White Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-s). Stands exist in the Tehachapi Mountains and on the eastern slopes above the Owens Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-f). Stands in the Cottonwood, Inyo, Grapevine, and Panamint Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004) contain wash scrub species such as <i>Salazaria mexicana.</i>  Stands in Last Chance Canyon of Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Stands exist in the upper desert/lower montane zone in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b), in San Felipe Valley, at the eastern edge of Volcan Mountain (Evens and San 2005), and in the lower parts of the Little San Bernardino Mountains in Joshua Tree National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2005). The related <i>Viguiera laciniata</i> appears to form stands in cismontane San Diego County.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Because this vegetation type covers large areas of the Colorado Desert/Peninsular Range borderland, it is important to understand its dynamics to answer management questions. </div>
</div>

    

    

